Passing on through the Middle Ages to modern times we read of the fascination which Virgil’s poems had for theologians such as Augustine and Bede, no less than for scholars like Scaliger, for critics like Voltaire, for politicians like Burke, for poets, essay- ists, orators, statesmen, without number. Two striking testimonies, above all, have been paid by great genius to his influence. One is the frequent imitation of his style in the language of Tacitus, the one great literary genius of Imperial Rome, and one of the greatest masters of expression in all literature. The other is the homage, as of a disciple to his master, which Dante pays to the genius of his countryman : ”

‘O degli altri poeti onore e lume, Vagliami‚ 'l lungo studio e ’l grande amore, Che m’ han fatto eercar lo tuo volume. Tu se' lo mio maestro, e 'l mio autore: Tu se' solo colui, da cu’ io tolsi , Lo bello stile, che m' ha fatto honore¹' (Inserno i. 85—87).
